I want to go directly to Canto 17 and then talk about what's going on.

593
01:03:27,361 --> 01:03:36,081
And now you've got to realize that scholars have only, don't try to read secondary sources about this, because they are all completely hopeless.

594
01:03:36,080 --> 01:03:40,241
Because somehow or other they've got the view that you can believe what Virgil says.

595
01:03:40,241 --> 01:03:45,601
And you could see already at the wall that Virgil doesn't understand what it was or why it was important.

596
01:03:45,600 --> 01:03:52,001
And now Virgil's explaining the whole structure of purgatory and of God and of love and everything.

597
01:03:52,000 --> 01:03:53,601
And he's all mixed up.

598
01:03:53,600 --> 01:03:58,081
And if you go to find any help from the critics, you're not, because they're all mixed up.

599
01:03:58,080 --> 01:04:04,081
And I can't fix it, but I can show you what he's trying to say and how it's mixed up.

600
01:04:04,080 --> 01:04:07,681
And also, maybe give you an account of why it's mixed up.

601
01:04:07,681 --> 01:04:09,121
Okay, let's see now.

602
01:04:10,040 --> 01:04:26,361
So here we are in the middle of purgatory, and what you're getting is some kind of mixture of Aristotle and Troubadour Christianity, somehow put together to try to explain everything that's going on.

603
01:04:26,361 --> 01:04:30,681
I mean, what I really think is there's no coherent way to put it together.

604
01:04:30,681 --> 01:04:46,921
It's not Dante's fault that you can't get Troubadour love of your lady together with Aristotle and Stoic views about desire and views about the total blissfulness of contemplating the supreme being.

605
01:04:46,921 --> 01:04:50,681
There are just too many balls in the air to keep track of.

606
01:04:51,241 --> 01:05:05,240
What I sort of reproach Dante for is that he doesn't signal the fact that Virgil is all mixed up until by the time he does, I'll try to show you that he does, but by that time we're all mixed up.

607
01:05:05,241 --> 01:05:07,000
So here's what the best I can do.

608
01:05:07,321 --> 01:05:18,520
So we discover you can't move at night, but after the sun goes down, you discover that different stars come out, starting on 181.

609
01:05:18,520 --> 01:05:25,001
We're now in Canto 17, line 70, roughly.

610
01:05:25,881 --> 01:05:30,120
And then now they discover they can't walk anymore.

611
01:05:30,120 --> 01:05:31,881
Our strength, why do you melt away?

612
01:05:31,881 --> 01:05:33,080
I said several times.

613
01:05:33,080 --> 01:05:36,281
They're in a different place than they were the previous night, I think, but doesn't matter.

614
01:05:36,281 --> 01:05:37,401
It's night again.

615
01:05:37,960 --> 01:05:48,520
And my legs were turning to lead, and they've gotten to a certain style and as a certain level.

616
01:05:48,521 --> 01:05:59,600
And now he asks Virgil, line 82, Dear Father, what impurity is washed in pain here, though our feet must stay, I beg you not to stay your speech.

617
01:05:59,601 --> 01:06:04,320
And he, and now he starts a big speech about how things are.

618
01:06:06,080 --> 01:06:11,921
They happen to be in the circle of sloth, which we'll come back to, but that's not what he's explaining right now.

619
01:06:11,921 --> 01:06:21,841
He says, and he says, now at line 85, that love of good which in life before lay idle in the soul is paid for now.

620
01:06:21,841 --> 01:06:24,561
Here, sloth strains at the once neglected oral.

621
01:06:24,641 --> 01:06:33,360
He's already telling you, sloth is sort of being too lazy, not, again, not passionate about anything, not caring enough about anything.

622
01:06:34,320 --> 01:06:43,520
But that you may more clearly know the way which your entire attention, give your entire attention to my words, and you shall gather good fruit from delay.

623
01:06:43,521 --> 01:06:47,440
We'll use this time we can't walk for Virgil to explain things.

624
01:06:47,441 --> 01:06:49,040
Now comes confusion.

625
01:06:49,040 --> 01:06:52,160
He says, neither creator nor his creatures.

626
01:06:52,160 --> 01:06:54,960
Now, what is he knowing about creator and creatures?

627
01:06:54,960 --> 01:06:57,520
He's supposed to be talking from antiquity.

628
01:06:57,521 --> 01:06:59,360
I've looked it up in the Italian.

629
01:06:59,360 --> 01:07:00,881
That's what it says.

630
01:07:00,881 --> 01:07:02,080
I don't know.

631
01:07:02,080 --> 01:07:04,960
I mean, it looks like, I don't know what it looks like.

632
01:07:04,960 --> 01:07:12,080
It looks like Dante's can't get it, can't keep clear track of what Virgil can know and what he can't know.

633
01:07:12,080 --> 01:07:14,240
And you'll see it happening again in a minute.

634
01:07:14,561 --> 01:07:21,761
He says, neither creature nor creator move as you well know, but in the action of animal or mind-directed love.

635
01:07:21,761 --> 01:07:28,640
Now that's funny, because he didn't know a little while before that you had to be in the sun in order to move.

636
01:07:28,641 --> 01:07:38,960
Now he says it's perfectly obvious as if, well, either he just learned it, which I don't think, or that anybody knows that you don't move except insofar as you love.

637
01:07:38,960 --> 01:07:43,000
Now then it becomes three stanzas of total confusion, I think.

638
01:07:43,000 --> 01:07:51,080
Natural love may never fall to error, the other may strive to good or bad ends by too little or too much fervor.

639
01:07:51,080 --> 01:07:56,680
Now, I don't know, that sounds like a story about misdirected love.

640
01:07:56,681 --> 01:08:01,801
And that's nice, except that's not an Aristotelian Virgil sort of thing.

641
01:08:01,801 --> 01:08:03,160
And then it gets even weirder.

642
01:08:03,160 --> 01:08:08,360
While it desires the eternal good, I don't even know if I should put you through this.

643
01:08:08,921 --> 01:08:13,640
Don't get upset and don't try to understand it, because it doesn't, it's all confused.

644
01:08:13,641 --> 01:08:19,721
The primal good is, or the eternal good is Aristotle's prime mover.

645
01:08:19,721 --> 01:08:23,400
There is a kind of God-like something in Aristotle.

646
01:08:23,400 --> 01:08:32,200
It's just not the God of the Christians, and it's not a God that you love, but it is somehow the mover of everything.

647
01:08:32,200 --> 01:08:35,080
And then you should love secondary goods in reason.

648
01:08:35,240 --> 01:08:45,400
Well, Virgil is talking mostly Christian-like, only sort of mapping it sort of into sort of semi-Aristotle talk.

649
01:08:45,400 --> 01:08:46,761
Oh, dear, I don't know.

650
01:08:46,761 --> 01:08:52,520
I shouldn't have even tried, but I'm going to read you one more paragraph, and then I'm going to say I don't know what to make of it.

651
01:08:52,521 --> 01:08:59,720
But when it turns to evil or shows more or less zeal in it aught for what is good, the creature turns on the Creator.

652
01:08:59,721 --> 01:09:04,040
You realize how all wrong that is for those three stanzas?

653
01:09:04,040 --> 01:09:07,480
That's not Virgil's and Aristotle's view.

654
01:09:07,481 --> 01:09:08,681
That's the Christian view.

655
01:09:08,681 --> 01:09:20,761
I've just been telling you, that you can love some things too much and some things too little, that you desire the primal good, and the creature can turn on the Creator.

656
01:09:20,761 --> 01:09:23,881
But he didn't understand how the creature could turn on the Creator.

657
01:09:23,881 --> 01:09:25,520
That was what was happening at the wall.

658
01:09:25,841 --> 01:09:34,480
So Virgil launches into this seemingly Christian story, and I don't get it.

659
01:09:36,080 --> 01:09:48,640
And then he says, on the top of 182, line 110, and since no being may exist alone and apart from the first being, whatever that is, by their nature, all beings lack the power to hate that one.

660
01:09:48,960 --> 01:09:56,640
Well, now he seems to think that now he's being like Virgil, sort of, because he doesn't understand the wall.

661
01:09:56,641 --> 01:09:58,480
He doesn't understand sin.

662
01:09:58,481 --> 01:10:06,240
He now has flipped over to the view that since God is desirable and fulfilling, no one could hate God.

663
01:10:07,360 --> 01:10:10,080
So now he's missing his story about sin.

664
01:10:10,561 --> 01:10:12,000
I shouldn't have launched into this.

665
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:13,921
Let me go to the punchline.

666
01:10:14,240 --> 01:10:16,960
Where does he get things wrong?

667
01:10:16,960 --> 01:10:18,400
I've got three minutes.

668
01:10:18,400 --> 01:10:20,160
Go to page 190.

669
01:10:20,481 --> 01:10:27,680
The final important thing for him is that you have the power to control your love.

670
01:10:27,681 --> 01:10:32,400
And that means to, let's go back to the bottom of 189.

671
01:10:32,721 --> 01:10:36,160
The crucial thing is in line 63.

672
01:10:36,160 --> 01:10:46,000
That is, what you just take line 63, that you, because you have reason, you can guard the threshold of consent.

673
01:10:46,320 --> 01:11:06,320
That Virgil thinks that since nothing in the world is really worthy of total love, your job to be a good person is to cut down your love to equal the relative lovableness of things.

674
01:11:06,320 --> 01:11:15,240
But being a Stoic, he thinks that the most important thing you've got is the willpower not to totally love anything.

675
01:11:15,881 --> 01:11:16,601
And that's right.

676
01:11:16,841 --> 01:11:18,520
Here Virgil is being consistent.

677
01:11:18,521 --> 01:11:39,400
I mean, he's being wrong in explaining the divine comedy, but he's consistent with his Stoic view that the highest thing you've got is the power not to go and adore anything, because nothing is worthy of total love and adoration.

678
01:11:39,400 --> 01:11:41,480
That's sort of the sadness of Virgil.

679
01:11:41,481 --> 01:11:43,801
That's why Virgil is in limbo.

680
01:11:43,801 --> 01:11:48,040
Now, one, I got, according to that clock, one minute.

681
01:11:48,040 --> 01:11:56,440
I said at the very end, Dante lets you in on the fact that at that point Virgil has gone wrong.

682
01:11:56,441 --> 01:11:58,360
And how does he let you in on it?

683
01:11:58,761 --> 01:12:04,280
Well, he says he was listening to Virgil, and what did he do listening to Virgil?

684
01:12:04,280 --> 01:12:08,280
He said he found himself falling to sleep, line 87.

685
01:12:09,000 --> 01:12:14,520
So since Virgil had answered my question so clearly, is he being ironic?

686
01:12:14,521 --> 01:12:15,560
I think so.

687
01:12:16,200 --> 01:12:20,921
My mind was rambling, I was rambling drowsy within my mind.

688
01:12:20,921 --> 01:12:27,801
So the first thing is, when somebody gives a good lecture, explaining things clearly, you don't go to sleep.

689
01:12:27,801 --> 01:12:32,680
I don't see anybody asleep here today, at least, happily.

690
01:12:33,080 --> 01:12:40,520
But if you do give a confused and over-the-head of and bad lecture, then people start to go to sleep.

691
01:12:40,521 --> 01:12:41,560
That's the first thing.

692
01:12:41,561 --> 01:12:45,400
Dante hears this whole story, and his response is to fall asleep.

693
01:12:45,400 --> 01:13:00,000
Secondly, it turns out that since they're on the level of sloth, the people who are always being done given the opposite of what they had before, these people who didn't love enough, are being made to be frantically energetic.

694
01:12:54,521 --> 01:13:01,360
So he was awakened.

695
01:13:01,601 --> 01:13:08,320
Now I'm 89, I'm going to stop, in an instant to a pack of people running towards us, a mob, they broke upon the mountain.

696
01:13:08,320 --> 01:13:10,480
And what are they saying in line 103?

697
01:13:10,481 --> 01:13:14,240
Faster, faster to be slow in love is to lose time.

698
01:13:14,240 --> 01:13:21,600
So Virgil is talking on the circle of sloth because he is a case of sloth, because he's slow in love.

699
01:13:21,601 --> 01:13:31,680
Because instead of saying you should soup up your love and direct it toward God, he's saying you should control your love and cut it down to how satisfying the world is.

700
01:13:31,681 --> 01:13:35,120
And there Virgil has gone completely wrong.

701
01:13:35,120 --> 01:13:37,600
At least it gets clear there.

702
01:13:37,601 --> 01:13:44,000
There's a while I don't understand it, but there I think you can see Dante repudiating Virgil's view.

703
01:13:44,000 --> 01:13:45,520
Okay, stop at that.
